cypress/support/commands.js:603-606:
  Cypress.Commands.add('waitForTransition', () => {
    cy.waitForBusy();      // expects #busy-indicator to APPEAR
    cy.waitForNotBusy();   // expects #busy-indicator to be gone
  });

Graph.js:792-806 only renders #busy-indicator when state.busy=true, wrapped in <Fade transitionDelay='800ms'>. A fast graph render legitimately never makes the indicator visible — so waitForBusy fails the spec even when the product is healthy. Mentioned in findings under 'Test Bugs #4'.

Fix: rewrite waitForTransition to be tolerant. Wait for the canvas to have its expected next state, OR wait for #busy-indicator to be gone, without requiring it to appear first.

Suggested:
  Cypress.Commands.add('waitForTransition', () => {
    // The busy indicator may appear briefly or not at all (Fade has 800ms transitionDelay
    // so quick renders never show it). Only require it to be absent at the end.
    cy.get('#busy-indicator').should('not.exist');
  });

If a spec genuinely needs to assert the busy indicator appeared (rare), call cy.waitForBusy() explicitly there.

## Implementation Steps
1. Read commands.js:595-606 and src/Graph.js:792-806.
2. Replace waitForTransition body with the not.exist version above; keep waitForBusy / waitForNotBusy as helpers for the rare case.
3. Run transition.spec.js (was 1/7) and rendering.spec.js (was 2/7) — failures attributable to waitForBusy should clear.
4. Add a one-line WHY comment above the new body referencing the 800ms Fade delay.

## Acceptance
- waitForTransition succeeds even when the busy indicator never visibly appears
- transition.spec.js and rendering.spec.js failures attributable to this assertion are gone
